data.content:
Use EF Core 7+'s `ExecuteUpdateAsync` and `ExecuteDeleteAsync` — they run directly as SQL without loading entities into memory:

```csharp
// Operation 1: Bulk update — single UPDATE statement, no entities loaded
await _db.Products
    .Where(p => p.LastSoldDate < DateTime.UtcNow.AddMonths(-6))
    .ExecuteUpdateAsync(s =>
        s.SetProperty(p => p.IsActive, false));

// Operation 2: Bulk delete — single DELETE statement, no entities loaded
await _db.AuditLogs
    .Where(l => l.CreatedAt < DateTime.UtcNow.AddYears(-1))
    .ExecuteDeleteAsync();
```

**Why this is faster:**
- Your original code loads 500K/2M rows into memory, tracks them all, then sends individual `UPDATE`/`DELETE` statements back
- These generate a **single SQL statement** executed server-side — no round-trips, no memory pressure, no change tracking

**Caveats:**
- These bypass the change tracker — any already-loaded entities won't reflect the changes. Call these before querying, or reload affected entities afterward
- No `SaveChangesAsync()` needed (or wanted) — execution is immediate
- If deleting 2M rows in one shot causes lock contention, batch it:

```csharp
int deleted;
do
{
    deleted = await _db.AuditLogs
        .Where(l => l.CreatedAt < DateTime.UtcNow.AddYears(-1))
        .Take(10_000)
        .ExecuteDeleteAsync();
} while (deleted > 0);
```
